There are three words which occur in different documents which seem to require some explanation— Skomerfore on page 873 Lovecopsty on page 1793 and Utviethis on page 264. Skomerfare occurs in Gower's Confessio Amantio, andin Halliwell's Dictionary is de- scribed as meaning piracy. The derivation is given as from assumeris, which certainly means piracy. This explanationis not altogether satisfactory, for Skomerfare is evidently a compouud word, and cannot be derived from escumm'e alone. ln the Dover Chamberlains’ Accounts the tolls levied on various imports are invariable uelled “fare,'' e.g., “Hokfaress’ “ Herringfare,” “Sprot- fare,” etc., and Skomerfare must accordingly bea toll levied on “Skomer.” The word occurs occasionally in the accounts, and it will not be out of place to quote one

or two instances of its use.

Et solut’ Iohanni Hannon pro qumfore — (Add. MSS„ Β.Μ., 29615, fol. 55).

Et in litteris deftrendis pro hominibus de Mergate . . . querendis pro voiagium de Skomesfore od diversas vices- iiis. iid. (ib. fol. aab).

If we derive the word from assumeris it would mean either the toll levied on all booty captured and landed out of pirate vessels, or, what is more probable, the proportion of profit which each mariner obtained as his share of the plunder. I am inclined to think the latter is the right local interpretation of the word, for the Warden, as the Admiral of the Cinque Forte, always claimed at least a share in the goods of pirates.
